{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_01SoAHV71H8szfn4ZR5wHpk2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Everything checks out. Summary of the fix:\n\n- **Root cause**: `prometheus-config` ConfigMap only had a scrape job for Prometheus itself — nothing targeting RabbitMQ. RabbitMQ's own config (`rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin on port 15692) and the `rabbitmq`/`rabbitmq-headless` Services were already correct.\n- **Fix** (edited the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap, no new resource types):\n  - Added a `rabbitmq` scrape job with static targets for the 3 pods' stable DNS names via the existing headless service (`rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local:15692`), scraping `/metrics`.\n  - Added a `rabbitmq_rules.yml` recording rule (`rabbitmq_up = up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}`) since the RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin doesn't emit a metric literally named `rabbitmq_up` — Prometheus's synthetic `up` metric isn't renamable via `metric_relabel_configs`, so a recording rule is the correct native mechanism.\n  - Reloaded via the already-enabled `--web.enable-lifecycle` `/-/reload` endpoint (no pod restart needed).\n- **Verified**: all 3 `rabbitmq` targets report `health: up`; `rabbitmq_up` query returns 3 samples (all value `1`); RabbitMQ cluster still shows all 3 nodes Running/healthy."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1883,"cache_read_input_tokens":67928,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1883},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c665d094-723b-45a6-a7d1-237117fa5ee6","uuid":"bfe2ba53-a0c0-428d-b2e3-ac8fdb7e4524","request_id":"req_011CcaiFCX3ZtGs2V8hAmJKM"}
